Introduction
People may wonder why backend engineers and data scientists still need to learn JavaScript in 2026. Shouldn’t we focus on LLMs and agentic AI instead? Absolutely — but not every data scientist has the opportunity to work on large-scale LLM training, which is extremely resource-intensive.
Agentic AI is another clear priority. But how can a data scientist demonstrate an orchestration design? By building a working demo — and that often requires JavaScript, including React and Next.js.
So let’s spend ten days becoming comfortable with JavaScript in the context of HTML and CSS. The greatest challenge is not the syntax or data structures, but understanding how JavaScript interacts with HTML and CSS.
Day 1 case
The following code can be saved as html file.
<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
body {
background: white;
color: black;
transition:
background 0.3s,
color 0.3s; /* smooth transition */
}
/* Apply these styles when the body element has the dark-mode class. */
body.dark-mode {
background: #1a1a2e;
color: #eee;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Dark Mode Demo</h1>
<button id="themeToggle">Toggle Theme</button> <script>
const btn = document.getElementById("themeToggle");
btn.addEventListener("click", () => {
document.body.classList.toggle("dark-mode");
// Update the button text based on the current state.
const isDark = document.body.classList.contains("dark-mode");
btn.textContent = isDark ? "Switch to Light Mode" : "Switch to Dark Mode";
});
</script>
</body>
</html>
Explanation

• HTML Structure
Let’s keep only the skeleton of the code so that the CSS and JavaScript components are easier to identify. The CSS appears in the <head>, while the JavaScript is placed inside the <body>. The <script> comes after the <button>, which makes sense because the JavaScript handles the user’s interaction with that button.
<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
<style> // CSS </style>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Dark Mode Demo</h1>
<button id="themeToggle">Toggle Theme</button>
<script> //JavaScript
</script>
</body>
</html>
2. CSS elements
<style>
body {
background: white;
color: black;
transition:
background 0.3s,
color 0.3s; /* smooth transition */
}
/* Apply these styles when the body element has the dark-mode class. */
body.dark-mode {
background: #1a1a2e;
color: #eee;
}
</style>Here, two CSS rulesets are defined: body and body.dark-mode. body is an element selector that targets the <body> element and defines the default light-theme styles. body.dark-mode is a combined selector (element + class) that targets a <body> element with the dark-mode class: <body class="dark-mode">.
3. JS method with DOM
<button id="themeToggle">Toggle Theme</button><script>
const btn = document.getElementById("themeToggle");
btn.addEventListener("click", () => {
document.body.classList.toggle("dark-mode");
// Update the button text based on the current state.
const isDark = document.body.classList.contains("dark-mode");
btn.textContent = isDark ? "Switch to Light Mode" : "Switch to Dark Mode";
});
</script>
After creating a button with the ID themeToggle, JavaScript retrieves a reference to it using document.getElementById(). The addEventListener() method then attaches a click event listener to the button and passes it a callback function. This listener runs in the user’s browser, and the browser invokes the callback whenever the user clicks the button.
here is the callback:
() => {
document.body.classList.toggle("dark-mode");
// Update the button text based on the current state.
const isDark = document.body.classList.contains("dark-mode");
btn.textContent = isDark ? "Switch to Light Mode" : "Switch to Dark Mode";
}EOF
